      h2 Day 11 - Thursday – Osaka
      p We left Kyoto in the morning and headed to Osaka. Our main reason for going to Osaka was to be close to the train to Mt. Koya the next day. The shinkansen was very quick but takes you to Shin-Osaka Station, which actually isn't the central part of Osaka called Namba. We had to take a subway to the Namba area. This was our first brush with transportation signage in Japanese only. Luckily, there was a worker near the ticket machines to assit us. Otherwise, we would have been stuck.
      p 
       ' We arrived at our hotel, 
       a href="http://www.hotelmonterey.co.jp/en/htl/grasmere_osaka/" target="_blank" title="Monterey Grasmere Osaka" Monterey Grasmere Osaka
       ' , too early to check in. We left our luggage and walked around. 
      p 
        ' Osaka like every other Japanese city we visited has a lot of shopping. It's consistently more than any we've seen in the US. We walked endlessly past shops and had lunch in an English pub. One of the main shopping streets is an almost 2-kilometer covered shopping arcade called 
        a href="http://www.shinsaibashi.or.jp/e/" target="_blank" title="Shinsaibashi-suji" Shinsaibashi-suji
        '  . Walking down this street, it seemed to go on forever. 
      p 
        ' We did a loop back towards the hotel and came through an area known as 
        a href="http://americamura.jp/en/" title="Amerikamura" target="_blank" Amerikamura
        '  (American Village.) It had an American vibe to it and reminded us of a place like the East Village. It had t-shirt shops, bars, and a definite artsy vibe. It was unique to other places in Japan 
      p We came back to the hotel, checked in, and hung around until it got dark. The room was beautiful and large and was probably the nicest we stayed at in Japan.  
